>melody

>riffs
>rhythm
>beat
>bassline
>textures
>energy
>emotion

Examples of disingenuous, contrived and pretentious reasons for appreciating music:

again that's fine, I think that's like 95%+ of what makes music good, I just think you saying it's pretentious or contrived is silly. Do you think a teenage girl listening to Swift is being pretentious if she says the lyrics are her favorite part? If these things don't add to the music for you, that's fine, but sometimes they make me enjoy music more. They might turn a good track into a great track.

When I'm listening to music, I'm experiencing it as a whole, including it's musical properties and lyrics, musicianship, etc. I guess I can try to separate the enjoyment I get from the former and the latter after the fact, but when I'm listening it's all just part of the experience I'm having. If I'm thinking about how much I enjoy different records, these things factor in. In fact it would be contrived of me to try and separate them because that's not part of the natural way I experience music.

>Would you enjoy listening to those exact same lyrics if a fat 12 year old was simply belching them a capella? Of course you wouldn’t, which proves that lyrics and thematic ideas are not music in and of themselves.

Of course not, because that would sound like shit. Whatever enjoyment I got from the lyrics would be completely overridden by the terrible sound. I'm not saying one or the other is better, they're both key for making the music good.

>most of the MUSIC sounds like shit
Okay well that's your opinion. I think the music itself is good, I like morissey's vocal melodies and the jangly guitars. The lyrics greatly add to the record though.

I am a big fan of their psychedelic phase. Robot Hive/Exodus was the best album IMO. The song structures are at their most unique. Not a single bad track on the whole album. The lyrics are weird and give off this really well thought out howl-esque beat poetry vibe, but more down to earth. It sounds like the whole thing was put together coming down of an acid trip and thinking about the way people just live together like rats in a major city. It's a genius construct of deconstructivism and social commentary. The whole thing is saying something and never actually sails the point home. It's transient beauty.

Neil if you are reading this excellent work friend.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114920586
You can, it's called chromaticism. But in most contexts it's not really a very efficient way of making music. Harmonically, you'll mostly be playing in musical consonants, which are notes that don't really sound like anything when played together, not bad, but not good either, just neutral.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114920586
Certain frequencies sound good together
Like any tone we call A sounds really good with C# and E but bad with D# and A#
Scales and modes are a way to know what we're gonna get through playing, whether its consonant or dissonant

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114920586
So that you can do a key change at the end and lift the entire song up

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114920586
If you want your music to be mostly consonant you'll naturally compose in a certain key. That's why ancient instruments tend to be tuned to simple pentatonic scales, basically the most consonant intervals that exist. But you can use chromatic notes, borrowed chords, modulations etc. to spice it up.

I feel it's more of an aesthetic game than anything. Plenty of "blackgaze" and "black metal" music share a lot of qualities of shoegaze, but are mostly disregarded as completely different (black metal) or as its own thing (black gaze). Early Alcest and Trautonist seem to be more of shoegaze, but are considered "black gaze". What? I am convinced it's all in the marketing and image, same thing with slowcore. Slowcorers look more like shoegazers, and as far as i'm aware, social media and the internet has pushed both these genres to a higher combined forefront. it makes sense..... dream pop, shoegaze and slowcore are more prettier music. black gaze is a silly thing, not entirely shoegaze and not entirely black metal. it just seems like "metal" or "pretty rock" , a lot of it to me it does. Deafheaven has a fancy pedalboard, a well-rounded drummer who can play patterns, and a gay dancing singer, but to me are neither shoegaze or black metal. It's just.... pretty music? what? they dress either suave or normally but what are they made out to be? BLACK METAL?? are you kidding me! It just confuses me how people choose which band goes into what folder on their computer.
lovesliescrushing is said to be like "mbv"... no? this is ambiance, not shoegaze. what is slowcore? slow dream-pop? that's kind of like shoegaze, and they dress more similar to shoegazers, kinda. I don't get it.

>>114919723
Keep looking for videos about triads.

And remember. One triad per string, then you slide with that shape up and down the fretboard looking for the right sound.
If you do it right, you'll be able to reach all notes. Sliding and keeping the shapes of the chords changes the root note, and the note in the root note of the shape is the note you're playing.


I think my explanation is confuse, but, you'll find a shape per string, six shapes per tone and a whole lot of scales. Remember that you need to use the right scale of the tone in the fretboard when you change the tone, so the 1, 3 and 5th notes are not in the C scale, but in the scale you choose.

Fun fact, there are a whole lot of scales, the Arabic, the jew scale and others. Each scale have its own tone.

Then we have modes and shit. But the logic is the same.

For each scale, many more shapes appear.

Rick was as much a member of Floyd in 1994 as he was in 1987: relegated to salaried musician. He even was thinking of pulling out of the project entirely. Retrospectively, David likes to champion the notion that he was all about supporting Rick post-Waters, but make no mistake David was his own tyrant when he gained full control in 1987 (iirc he sided with Roger in evicting him from the band in 1978). A partial truth. Waters was annoyed Gilmour used his musical ideas in his solo album in 1978, and for the writing of The Wall and The Final Cut, Dave had minimal ideas to contribute despite complaining to Waters his ideas weren't being used. Waters told him to come up with ideas, but Gilmour (like Wright), generally were unhurried and unambitious creatively speaking. Waters was prolific; Bob Ezrin once said Roger was great to work with because if something wasn't working in a song he'd nix it and try something else. He wasn't precious with his ideas and open to scrutiny. Roger certainly wasnt waiting for anyone.

Rick was dragging his heels in the production of The Wall, he was sailing his yacht and being obstinate. The band had a sizeable tax debt and deadlines were cut-throat. Rick told Roger to fuck off; Roger threatened to pull the album completely unless Rick left. They were in financial jeopardy. So Rick was vetoed out.

Dave doesn't like to admit this, but it's a part of the band history. He had no ideas to contribute and would likely need years to come up with more song ideas (which is why he co-wrote with so many collaborators for AMLOR. He had no idea where he was going.

Nick also played on every song on The Final Cut, save for the final track, Two Suns. Nick cannot play outside of 4/4 (save for Money in 7/4).

From an audio perspective, analog filters are the main thing software can’t reproduce well.

I'd just like to point out that my mom saw Rachmaninoff play when she was in high school and, while that only means that I'm an old fart, the mildly entertaining aspect of this is the reactions she got from her co-workers and peers in the '70s and '80s.

Mom was born in 1921 and her parents took her see him playing with the Cleveland Symphony sometime in the late '30s. When we moved to San Francisco in the early '70s (I was in high school then), we fell in with a group of younger coworkers at mom's law firm who were classical fans and we went to the winter Symphony concerts with them once in awhile. One show featured Piano Concerto #2, damned if I can recall who the soloist was. Anyway, mom mentioned in passing that she had seen him perform this very piece back when and her coworkers were simply stunned. So mom chided them a little about it and went with, "all that means is that I'm old". She was in her early '50s then, so clearly "not all that old" at all.

>>114840634
if you want to approach it "naively" then actively look for different periods of classical music, listen to a few, and if you like them look for more works written in the same period or musical style, maybe for different organics or by composers from different parts of the world
if you want to approach it more technically read "Harmony" by Walter Piston
>song
a song is a piece of music for voice or voices, whether accompanied or not, and most contemporary classical pieces, and also most pieces written in the last ~1000 years, are not songs, so that's why the more generic "piece" term is used
>so many violins
violin is indeed a popular instrument, together with the whole string section, though in contemporary classical, because of a number of practical constraints, it's not as popular as it was 100 years ago
it wasn't as popular as guitar in rock, especially because rock is an aesthetic which heavily relies on the (distorted) electric guitar while violin is more of a convention in classical music, which can very well still be classical music without strings
>I'm tired of it
go listen to some piano sonatas, solo percussion pieces, opera or anything else where the violin is absent or not prominent
>cannons and shit
that's just one specific instance, cannons are astronomically uncommon in music

The very difficulty of thus applying Beethovenian Music to the Shakespearian Drama might lead, when conquered, to the utmost perfecting of musical Form, through its final liberation from each remaining fetter. What still distressed our great German poets in regard of Opera, and what still left its manifest traces on Beethoven's instrumental music, that scaffolding which in nowise rested on the essence of Music, but rather on that selfsame tendence which planned the operatic aria and the ballet−tune, this conventional four−square structure, so wondrously wreathed already with the luxuriant life of Beethovenian melody, would vanish quite away before an ideal ordering of highest freedom; so that Music now would take the ineffably vital shape of a Shakespearian drama, and its sublime irregularity, compared with the antique drama, would wellnigh give it the appearance of a nature−scene as against a work of architecture, a scene whose skilful measurement would be evinced by nothing but the unfailing sureness of the artwork's effect. Then would the greatest dramatist have taught us to fix that impromptu too; for in the highest conceivable Artwork the sublimest inspirations of them both should live with an undying life, as the essence of the world displayed with clearness past all measure in the mirror of the world itself.

Interviewer: Just before I left London, I heard a piece of music of yours, Fanfare for the Common Man, which had been taken by a rock group Emerson, Lake & Palmer. How do you feel about that?

Copland: Well, (laughs) of course it's very flattering to have one's music adopted by so popular a group, and so good a group as Emerson, Lake & Palmer. A lot depends on what they do with what they take, and naturally since I have a copyright on such material, they're not able to take it without my permission; so that in each case, where I have given my permission, there was something that attracted me about the version that they perform, which made me think I'd like to allow them to release it. Of course, I always prefer my own version best, but (laughs) what they do is really around the piece, you might say, rather than a literal transposition of the piece, and they're a gifted group. In that particular case, I allowed it to go by because when they first play it, they play it fairly straight and when they end the piece, they play it very straight. What they do in the middle, I'm not sure exactly how they connect that with my music but (laughs) they do it someway, I suppose. But the fact that at the beginning and the end it really is the Fanfare for the Common Man gave me the feeling I ought to allow them to do it as they pleased.

Interviewer: I know your original work is just over three minutes and Emerson, Lake & Palmer have managed to turn it into a nine minute work.

Copland: (Laughs) Exactly, well, it's those six minutes in the middle...(laughs)

>>114897390
Ok. Yes' first two albums are pretty good. Solid material. More akin to the likes of King Crimson or Genesis, but still unique.
The Yes Album was their breakthrough album
that introduced their more recognizable sound. Every album from The Yes Album to Tales from Topographic Oceans began to embrace more orchestral and prog sounds. Many consider Close to The Edge to be their best album, because despite there only being three songs, they are long and have a LOT of variety, plus fantastic vocals and musicianship. Some people like Tales from Topographic Oceans more, due to the larger focus on meandering orchestral/instrumental bits, but many people consider this to be padding and boring, you decide. After Tales from Topographic Oceans, their next four albums vary in quality. I haven't listened to Relayer yet, so I couldn't say. Going For The One is great, and has some very catchy songs. Tormato has about three good tracks, while the rest of it is just okay. Drama, on the other hand, is the most rock-oriented Yes album, and is fantastic. Four fantastic tracks with two great accompanying songs. 90125 is one of the best pop rock albums ever, simply because the Yes lineup is so talented. Big Generator is basically Yes's attempt to relive the popularity of 90125, but it's a bit worse. After that, the band had constant turnover, so don't go further unless you really like the band. I have heard that The Quest, their newest album, is actually pretty good, though. Maybe give that a try.

Basically:
Yes's first two albums are solid. Their next three albums are fantastic. Tales splits the community, listen to it after you have listened to The Yes Album and Close To The Edge, then decide if you like it. The four albums after tales vary in quality. I'd suggest Going For The One and Drama. After that, 90125 is great.

This is all from personal experience, take it with a grain of salt. I'm a retarded college student with his dad's music collection on his phone.

part of the reason it's harder to find good korean music is because when rock was getting popular in korea, a punk band invited some friend idiots on a music show and they jumped around with their dongs out on public weekend TV. It was a major scandal and got the show it was on canceled and a big stigma grew around band music. Music Shows are a big part of how the public and international fans get exposed (kek) to new music, so it really kneecapped the growth. It's coming back now but it's taken like a decade.

This is the producer behind what was arguably the most successful kpop song of 2022 and one of the most successful songs of 2023 so far (Hype Boy and Ditto by NewJeans, respectively, both really good).
After working as a producer for big kpop groups for years he released his first solo album in 2022 (a few months before working with NewJeans).
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZHbnVPDsYX8
It's essentially a concept album that serves as an homage to ppongjjak (an energetic, over-the-top, extremely tacky subgenre of Korean techno/synth-pop music) and other similar subgenres. It's a fun listen.

Memorize 3 chords and play them over and over in as many different combinations as you can. Change the strum pattern, the rhythm, which chord comes first, or even the intensity at which you play each chord.

You can definitely learn to play an instrument very will starting at late 20s or even 30s. You just don't usually see that because most of the people who have a real passion for it discovered it young and practiced obsessively from an earlier age. But there's no absolute reason why you can't reach that level if you start obsessively practicing now, it's just not typical that people discover something they're truly that passionate about that late in life.

Most instrumentalists reach a plateau once they figure they're "good enough" to do what they want to do and have the chops they need. Typically they'll reach that plateau after a few years, unless they're trying to be a world renowned virtuoso. You can probably reach that plateau by the time you're 30.

EPs used to be 7" records with more tracks than a single, then they were 12" records around 12-15 minutes. Albums were full-sized 12" records of around 45 minutes or more.
Nowadays that means fuck all because there's basically no difference between EP and Album besides the amount of tracks.

Also singles are simply single tracks released to promote a bigger release or just as a tiny standalone release.

Oracle was considered an EP I think. 2 tracks, 34 minutes - but then there's a bonus 46-minute-long track.
Sunn O))) releases are mostly called albums, but it's because "album" is the most general term for anything that is not a singular track shorter than 10 minutes. A distinction they do make is
>studio record
>live record
